  Warning                                                         6000 1451   71
==================================================================6000 1451   72
  MF/MT combinations used to define ALL electron interaction data 6000 1451   73
  are newly defined MF/MT numbers for ENDF/B-VI that did not exist6000 1451   74
  in earlier versions of ENDF/B.                                  6000 1451   75
==================================================================6000 1451   76
  Definition of Data                                              6000 1451   77
==================================================================6000 1451   78
  Cross Sections (MF=23)                                          6000 1451   79
==================================================================6000 1451   80
1) The total electron interaction cross section is given          6000 1451   81
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/501. It is the sum of scatter,          6000 1451   82
   bremsstrahlung, excitation and ionization cross sections,      6000 1451   83
   i.e., MT = 526, 527, 528, and 534 through 572.                 6000 1451   84
2) The total electron ionization cross section is given           6000 1451   85
   explicitly as MF/MT=23/522. It is the sum of the aubshell      6000 1451   86
   cross sections, i.e., all MT = 534 through 572.                6000 1451   87
==================================================================6000 1451   88
  Angular and Energy Distributions (MF=26)                        6000 1451   89
==================================================================6000 1451   90
3) For Large Angle Scatter (MT=525), angular distributions of     6000 1451   91
   electrons are tabulated between cosine = -1.0 and 0.999999.    6000 1451   92
   Between +0.99999 and +1.0 it is analytically defined as        6000 1451   93
   Coulomb scattering,                                            6000 1451   94
                                                                  6000 1451   95
   d(sig)/d(cos) = A/[eta+(1.0 - cos)]^2                          6000 1451   96
                                                                  6000 1451   97
   where the shielding parameter (eta) is defined by the          6000 1451   98
   Steve Seltzer expression (see, ref. 1), and (A) is the         6000 1451   99
   normalization factor for the integral +0.99999 to +1.0.        6000 1451  100
   Electron elastic scatter means no energy loss, so only         6000 1451  101
   angular distributions are giving.                              6000 1451  102
4) For bremsstrahlung, both the outgoing electron and photon are  6000 1451  103
   described. The photon energy spectra are given, but angular    6000 1451  104
   distributions are not; these can be analytically defined by a  6000 1451  105
   number of different methods. For the electron, average energy  6000 1451  106
   loss is given. The electron is assumed to continue along its   6000 1451  107
   original direction of travel, so angular distributions are not 6000 1451  108
   given. WARNING - bremsstrahlung is a three body process,       6000 1451  109
   involving an electron, a photon, and an atom - so that you     6000 1451  110
   cannot use energy or momentum correlation to simply relate     6000 1451  111
   the secondary electron and the emitted photon.                 6000 1451  112
5) For excitation, the average energy loss of the electron is     6000 1451  113
   given. The electron is assumed to continue along its original  6000 1451  114
   direction of travel, so angular distributions are not given.   6000 1451  115
6) For Ionization, the spectra of electrons is given. The electron6000 1451  116
   is assumed to continue along its original direction of travel, 6000 1451  117
   so angular distributions are not given. In ionization two      6000 1451  118
   identical electrons emerge; the incident electron, and an      6000 1451  119
   electron ejected by the atom [thereby ionizing the atom]. Since6000 1451  120
   the two particles are indistinquishable, we define the electron6000 1451  121
   with the lower energy to be that ejected by the atom, and the  6000 1451  122
   electron with the higher energy to be the incident electron.   6000 1451  123
   The energy of the two electrons is exactly correlated by energy6000 1451  124
   conservation: initial incident electron energy = binding energy6000 1451  125
   of the ejected electron, plus the kinetic energy of the ejected6000 1451  126
   and the secondary incident electron. Therefore only the spectra6000 1451  127
   of the lower energy, ejected electron is given. The energy of  6000 1451  128
   the secondary incident electron should be defined to conserve  6000 1451  129
   energy, as described above. The energy lost by the incident    6000 1451  130
   electron is the sum of the binding and kinetic energy of the   6000 1451  131
   ejected electron.                                              6000 1451  132
7) Relaxation of ionized atoms back to neutrality is not described6000 1451  133
   here; it is described in the companion Evaluated Atomic Data   6000 1451  134
   Library (EADL).                                                6000 1451  135
